<article>

  <h2>Context</h2>

  <p>
    The Sammādiṭṭhi
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sutta" data-en="discourse">Sutta</span> (MN 9)
    is unusual in the Majjhima
    <span class="pali" data-pali="nikāya" data-en="collection">Nikāya</span>:
    it is not the Buddha's teaching but Sāriputta's. The elder monk, regarded
    in the canon as foremost in
    <span class="pali" data-pali="paññā" data-en="wisdom">paññā</span>, gives
    the discourse to a group of monks. At the end, the monks ask the Buddha to
    confirm it. He does so, adding that anyone who understood what Sāriputta
    had said "will have broken through to right view and arrived at this true
    Dhamma."
  </p>

  <p>
    The sutta opens with a simple claim: a noble disciple who has
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sammādiṭṭhi" data-en="right view">sammādiṭṭhi</span>
    — right view — has a view that is "straight," has arrived at true
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dhamma" data-en="the teaching; phenomena">Dhamma</span>,
    and has "arrived here at this true Dhamma." This is the first factor of the
    Noble Eightfold Path, but it is also described as the condition that makes all
    the other factors work. The question MN 9 then addresses is: what does right
    view actually mean, in practice?
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>The Structure of the Sutta</h2>

  <p>
    Sāriputta's method is repetitive by design. He takes a series of topics —
    wholesome and unwholesome, nutriment, suffering, aging-and-death, and more —
    and applies the same four-part analysis to each:
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "When a noble disciple understands the unwholesome, the root of the unwholesome,
    the wholesome, and the root of the wholesome — in that way, he is one of right view."
    <cite>— MN 9 (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    The formula: understand the thing, understand its origin, understand its cessation,
    understand the path to its cessation. This is the same structure as the four noble
    truths — which is not coincidental. Right view, applied to any subject, produces
    the same result: a clear seeing of what a thing is, how it comes to be, how it
    ceases, and how that ceasing is brought about.
  </p>

  <p>
    Topics covered in the sutta include: the unwholesome and wholesome
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="akusala" data-en="unwholesome">akusala</span> and
    <span class="pali" data-pali="kusala" data-en="wholesome">kusala</span>);
    the four types of nutriment
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="āhāra" data-en="nutriment">āhāra</span>);
    suffering (<span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>);
    and then, working backward through the twelve links of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="paṭicca-samuppāda" data-en="dependent origination">paṭicca-samuppāda</span>:
    aging-and-death, birth, becoming, clinging, craving, feeling, contact, the six
    sense bases, name-and-form, consciousness, formations, and ignorance. The sutta
    ends with the taints.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Sāriputta's Method</h2>

  <p>
    The structure of the sutta is not merely an organizational convenience. Sāriputta
    is not listing topics and defining them; he is enacting a way of seeing. The
    four-part formula — thing, origin, cessation, path — applied to topic after topic
    is a demonstration of what right view looks like in operation. By the time the
    sutta has applied it sixteen times, the pattern has been internalized through
    repetition rather than simply explained.
  </p>

  <p>
    The pairing of opposites throughout — unwholesome and wholesome, suffering and
    its cessation, ignorance and its abandonment — is also deliberate. Right view
    does not operate by knowing one side of a pair; it knows both. To understand
    craving requires understanding what craving gives rise to and what the cessation
    of craving would mean. A person who knows only that craving is harmful has a
    view; a person who knows its origin, its cessation, and the path to that cessation
    has right view.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Right View and Dependent Origination</h2>

  <p>
    The central section of MN 9 works through the twelve links of dependent origination
    in reverse order. Beginning with aging-and-death and working backward to ignorance,
    Sāriputta applies the four-part formula to each link. The result is an account of
    dependent origination not as a theoretical chain but as a map for investigation:
    each link is presented as something that can be known directly — its nature, where
    it comes from, what its cessation is, what practice leads to that cessation.
  </p>

  <p>
    The sutta thus provides a bridge between the abstract structure of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="paṭicca-samuppāda" data-en="dependent origination">paṭicca-samuppāda</span>
    and the practical work of the path. Understanding dependent origination is not an
    intellectual exercise in this framing; it is the exercise of right view applied
    to the actual texture of experience. Each link — craving, clinging, becoming,
    contact — is something that can be observed, whose arising and cessation can
    be understood from inside the observation.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>The Ending: The Taints</h2>

  <p>
    The sutta ends not with ignorance but with the
    <span class="pali" data-pali="āsavā" data-en="taints; fermentations">āsavas</span>
    — the deep-rooted taints or fermentations that the canon identifies as the
    condition for ignorance itself. The three āsavas are sensual desire
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="kāmāsava" data-en="taint of sensual desire">kāmāsava</span>),
    desire for existence
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="bhavāsava" data-en="taint of becoming">bhavāsava</span>),
    and ignorance
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="avijjāsava" data-en="taint of ignorance">avijjāsava</span>).
    Their abandonment is the definition of full liberation.
  </p>

  <p>
    Sāriputta applies the same formula: a noble disciple understands the āsavas,
    their origin, their cessation, and the path to their cessation. With that
    understanding — not just as a proposition but as a direct seeing — the mind
    is liberated. The sutta closes with the familiar declaration: such a person
    is freed through non-clinging.
  </p>

  <p>
    The ending is structurally significant. Right view applied to the āsavas means
    seeing the very taints that sustain ignorance, knowing how they arise, and
    knowing what their cessation would mean. The implication is that right view,
    practiced fully, turns on itself — it is the condition that, when mature enough,
    sees through the last obscuration. The path begins with right view, and what
    it ends with is right view working on its own root.
  </p>

</article>
